  "local_port": 48768,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How do I send 16-bit data to Arduino using Simulink?",
  "response": "To send 16-bit data to an Arduino using Simulink, you'll need to follow these steps. This process involves setting up your Simulink model to communicate with the Arduino board using the Arduino Support Package for Simulink.\n\n### Step-by-Step Guide:\n\n1. **Install the Arduino Support Package**:\n   - Open MATLAB.\n   - Go to the Home tab and click on \"Add-Ons\".\n   - Search for \"Arduino Support from MATLAB and Simulink\" and install it.\n   - Follow the installation prompts to complete the setup.\n\n2. **Create a New Simulink Model**:\n   - Open MATLAB and type `simulink` in the command window to open Simulink.\n   - Create a new model by selecting \"Blank Model\".\n\n3. **Add the Arduino Block**:\n   - Drag and drop an \"Arduino Due\" or \"Arduino Uno\" block from the Simulink Library Browser under \"Simulink Support Package for Arduino Hardware\" -> \"Arduino\".\n\n4. **Configure the Arduino Block**:\n   - Double-click on the Arduino block to open its parameters.\n   - Select your Arduino board type (e.g., Arduino Uno or Arduino Due).\n   - Choose the correct serial port for your Arduino.\n\n5. **Add a 16-bit Data Source**:\n   - Drag and drop a \"Constant\" block from the Simulink Library Browser.\n   - Double-click on the Constant block and set its value to the desired 16-bit integer.\n   - Ensure the data type is set to `int16` or `uint16` depending on whether you need a signed or unsigned 16-bit integer.\n\n6. **Add a Serial Transmit Block**:\n   - Drag and drop a \"Serial Transmit\" block from the Simulink Library Browser under \"Simulink Support Package for Arduino Hardware\" -> \"Arduino\" -> \"Communication\".\n   - Connect the output of the Constant block to the input of the Serial Transmit block.\n   - Double-click on the Serial Transmit block and configure it to send 16-bit data. Set the \"Data type\" to `int16` or `uint16`.\n\n7. **Connect Blocks**:\n   - Connect the Constant block to the Serial Transmit block.\n   - Connect the Serial Transmit block to the Arduino block.\n\n8. **Run the Simulation and Deploy to Arduino**:\n   - Click on \"Run\" to simulate the model.\n   - If the simulation is successful, go to the \"Hardware\" tab in Simulink and click on \"Deploy to Hardware\".\n   - The model will be compiled and uploaded to your Arduino board.\n\n9. **Arduino Code Verification (Optional)**:\n   - You can verify the code generated for the Arduino by going to the \"Code\" tab in Simulink and selecting \"Generate Code\".\n   - This will show you the C code that will run on the Arduino.\n\n### Example Model Setup:\n\nHere's a basic example of how your Simulink model might look:\n\n- **Constant Block**: Set to a 16-bit value, e.g., `32767` for `int16`.\n- **Serial Transmit Block**: Configured to transmit `int16` data.\n- **Arduino Block**: Configured for your specific Arduino board and serial port.\n\n### Arduino Side:\n\nOn the Arduino side, you can read the 16-bit data using the Serial Monitor or write a simple sketch to process it. Here's a basic example of an Arduino sketch to read 16-bit data:\n\n```cpp\nvoid setup() {\n  Serial.begin(9600); // Set baud rate to match Simulink configuration\n}\n\nvoid loop() {\n  if (Serial.available() >= 2) { // 16-bit data is 2 bytes\n    int16_t data = Serial.read() | (Serial.read() << 8);\n    Serial.print(\"Received 16-bit data: \");\n    Serial.println(data);\n  }\n}\n```\n\nBy following these steps, you should be able to successfully send 16-bit data from Simulink to an Arduino board.",
